The architects saw in - the office also includes a kindergarten
The office building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Designn.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten here, with all that it includes: colorful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini-playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to the staff of Arch.Design since last year.
The project and architecture office Arch.Design, from which a whole series of well-known Brno buildings come, calculated from the first designs for the new building Avriopoint with the premises for its company mini-kindergarten.
In a wise way, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby tree age and the company is due to the fact that the project students return to their work as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility of working short, the kindergarten is another bonus that Art.Design has to offer to its employees in the concept of its social program.
The construction engineers have so much easier to reconcile their demanding profession and child care.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the staff of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they managed to gain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The minimum farm is financed by the European Social Fund and the State budget of the Czech Republic through the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment Policy.
This funding (grants of CZK 2, 8 million) has enabled the necessary facilities and equipment to be acquired and for a period of 2 years qualified staff and operations are provided.
After the use of the funding (2 years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took place for a whole year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the application process.
The children take care of fully qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, the kindergarten can visit children without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, but the day is different over several children.
The kindergarten business is flexible to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in terms of the use of the kindergarten - without regard to the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is a matter of individual education and care, the content of the programme in the mini-kindergarten is still comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children are not only playing here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school education, they are also learning English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What is more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and thus the stress is not taken away when the children are late to pick up from a far away kindergarten.
The parents are therefore more productive in their working time.
No wonder there are also natural and loyal relations between employers and workers.
Arch.Design thus joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in the recruitment of new employees, which are family-friendly and through such programmes strengthen their personal marketing.
A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interior of Gaudi
The roof mutates like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are reared fish mowers.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house was given the nickname "Bone House" with its organic forms.
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splits and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of the scales and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features for the youth style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with beautiful lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only with a more accurate look that you can see that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-through order.
During the night the whole facade is even more plastic, dramatic and the special lighting still strengthens the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and faded forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy-shaped wood copies the window frames, railing, decorative elements of doors, even watch holes and bars.
The house of Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the conversion of a house from 1877, which was carried out by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed to the idea of Gaudí's unusual and even cheaper conversion.
The rental house Casa Batlló, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its zipper that the decorations were created for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade was his idea.
However, many other artists and artists were also involved in the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
For example, Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the park Güell, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given the name "Bone House" by the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "glowing house."
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, the patron of Catalonia, is shown at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, which was unique for the time being, with ventilation channels and typical cams.
A little bizarre is already adjusting her 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations at that time and was not able to be accompanied by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permit from the city, but the information he provided on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later the city fathers were so horrified at the completion that they asked for remedy.
Among other things, the Council's leaders also met with the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there was no change, on the contrary - only 15 days after the call of the city district in this respect, Josep Batlló made an application for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was given to him promptly.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the conversion all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could easily chat without having to give up a certain intimacy in more confidential discussions.
The house was also given a rather unusual roof and two other floors by the construction of Gaudí's new façade.
Gaudí's game with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is covered and the lighthouses, is also impressive.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply used the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The owners of the house decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the 150.birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly acceptable business, it was kept to the visits, and it was also extended to other common and the roof-floor rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price to visit the building is not, however, a parrot, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Anyone who wants to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with his dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the house residents and visit him at home.
