The second sign set the Central European country when Merkel's decision to save Greece was a painful one.
This was strongly criticised at the time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel comes out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be saved while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was designed as an anti-European one, as it was driving the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
But their proposal, although somewhat sweetened, was adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures are to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the countries that are in conflict will be severely punished, can be forced to declare themselves unable to pay and, in this case, the private sector will have to pay part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard growth course, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as was mentioned by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do bad not to understand.
It is not just a question of reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will pass in more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the large companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures from yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has prepared its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like it would change anything.
Among the options that are being considered, it is that we should not be excluded from the euro area that is full of little serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and rule-abiding
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventive spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The exclusion of two real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsporty act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will perform the required penalty at the next game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next stage without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate about the case presented is that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who in his hymn of nobility and honor, and who had punished his players for similar events on other occasions) played the main role, and the drama by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history than theatrical and provocative technicians.
In any case, the debate is about whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions are a rule-abiding approach. In fact, this approach is based on the statutes of sport, but it seems to be circumventing its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused by the spirit of sport should be investigated.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players draw an unjustified benefit from the counterteam. That also did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually mean by misplay or bypassing the rule, because the circumference of the rule was not secretly executed in order to avoid a penalty, but should be as conspicuous as possible to be punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and welcomed the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage did the opponents draw from the deliberate fouls.
Here it should be stressed that the rival has not been placed in a less favourable position or benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue to play with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that the players start the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually also get out of the game. In addition, the players will get a penalty with this approach and go to the second card cycle, in which they are leaving for card accumulation with a card less than in the first cycle.
This does not make it so clear whether it is really an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (that would actually be a clear case of rule-abiding), they would rather choose when they would submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or fleeing from a punishment.
Although the limit between the gift of invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of the gift of invention.
I have the impression that the polemic was created by two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provocative transfer of rules.
The damage that has been done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
