Worldwide plan for the renewal of the lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFCs), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved in order to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the specific major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction obligations of the developed countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the FCKW released on earth due to the lighting, if the white-glowing pears, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or even better, by light-emitting diodes (LED).
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
Last year, in Copenhagen, the major exhaust gas issuers, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global emissions of CFCs from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, it would be necessary to deduct 5 Gt from this balance sheet to stabilise the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020, in order to prevent it from going out of control.
In the white-glowing pears, 95% of the energy is in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact light bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED light bulbs, this energy demand is reduced again by two times.
The compact light bulbs hold on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those which Philips has put on the market this week - this society has, by the way, taken part in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and use 80% less energy than a white light bulb, which is an indication of the savings of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that its completely new light bulbs give very little heat, they can also work with a rule resistance.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact light bulbs have reserves as they contain mercury and that they need to be disposed of as a special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except that the producers provide a point of acceptance.
The main source of mercury emissions on the planet, however, according to the report, is not the compact light bulb, but rather the coal power plants, which are emitting much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-glowing pears.
In the United States alone, these coal power plants release 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in the purchase of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 coal power plants, which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
