Alarm - Pesticides taken from children
A 10-year-old child takes on various chemical substances over the day 81, so a study published this Wednesday by the Générations Futures Association (former movement to protect the rights and respect of coming generations).
The association, which explains that its results "in the light of the small number of samples analysed do not represent a statistically significant value, but are an illustration of the problem being addressed," had bought between July and September the food usually consumed within four, from a about ten-year-old child to meals, plus an intermediate meal in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals, including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three milk products and 1.5 litres of water per day, have been examined as well as the dry-cleaning of laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is degrading: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptive factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded in the near whole of the cases, it is very well taken from this survey that the reality in which the consumer may be exposed to carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruptive factors is worrying," the association notes.
At breakfast alone, butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the possible carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that may affect the hormone system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended for the study as an intermediate meal, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, including lunch, where the study has identified traces of a strictly prohibited insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the hacksteak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were also spilled.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak with 34 chemical residues was the "richest," and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer is likely to be undervalued, "the study says.
The "Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts" (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the light of the urgency of the situation," to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in diseases of civilization."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables, which are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
